fields.page_description: An incredible architectural experience of The Tower of Bethlehem, and The Jeronimos Monastery, the objects of UNESCO World Heritage Site. An opportunity to see Portugal's rich maritime heritage and cultural treasures.
fields.name: Belem Small Group Walking Tour
fields.why_title: Why BookBelem Small Group Walking Tour With One Day Tours
fields.why_subtitle: Explore the stunning beauty of Portugal with our unforgettable experiences. Make a journey through history and times begin.
fields.info_subtitle: Enjoy a lovely walking tour in one of the most incredible areas in Lisbon  Belem, the significant landmark of the Age of Discoveries.
fields.short_description: An incredible architectural experience of The Tower of Bethlehem, and The Jeronimos Monastery, the objects of UNESCO World Heritage Site. An opportunity to see Portugal's rich maritime heritage and cultural treasures.
fields.full_description: We invite you to join this experience to see incredible architectural structures from the 16th century that have earned the status of UNESCO World Heritage Site – The Tower of Bethlehem, and The Monastery of Saint Jerome! But the list of historical treasures is not limited by that, as Belem is keeping a lot of other significant structures, the creation of which is dated back to the International Exhibit of 1940

fields.page_title: Lisbon: Sesimbra Castle & Espichel Cape Experience
fields.page_description: The unforgettable visit to the Castle of Sesimbra, framed by the ancient walls and surrounded by picturesque oceanfront views. A great chance to witness the astonishing Espichel Cape, a natural gem that can't be missed!
fields.name: Lisbon: Sesimbra Castle & Espichel Cape Experience
fields.why_title: Why Book Sesimbra Castle Experience With One Day Tours
fields.why_subtitle: Explore the stunning beauty of Portugal with our unforgettable experiences. Make a journey through history and times begin.
fields.info_title: The Castle and Coastal Town of Sesimbra & Espichel Cape!
fields.info_subtitle: Enjoy the natural wonders of Cape Espichel, an incredible natural attraction on the south side of Lisbon, and feel the atmosphere of coastal Sesimbra.
fields.short_description: The unforgettable visit to the Castle of Sesimbra, framed by the ancient walls and surrounded by picturesque oceanfront views. A great chance to witness the astonishing Espichel Cape, a natural gem that can't be missed!
fields.title_description: The Castle and Coastal Town of Sesimbra & Espichel Cape
fields.full_description: Within this experience, visit the Castle of Sesimbra along with the charming beach town surrounding it. There you will be able to try Portuguese cuisine and see the wonders of the Portuguese coastline! The final spot of the trip is the Espichel Cape, an astonishing natural gem that cannot be missed!

fields.full_description: Within this experience, we'll visit two of the most important palaces in Portugal’s recent history. The Palace of Queluz is an object of admiration not only because of its architecture but also because of the beautiful French gardens surrounding it. After that, we will taste the exquisite Portuguese seafood at Ericeira. The next stop is the Palace-Convent of Mafra, a protected World Heritage Site by UNESCO, and a great example of the Baroque period in Portugal.

Get ready for an exciting and active adventure with us. After pick up from your hotel, we will depart from Lisbon to Evora by a picturesque road with breathtaking views. We guarantee that your time on the road with our experienced guide will fly by as your comfort is our priority.

Our tour will begin in the gardens of the former palace of King Manuel. There, we will also be able to see the ruins of the palace, which is a great example of Mudejar architecture, a unique object on the Iberian Peninsula.

Our next stop is the most interesting and unusual work in Portuguese history  Saint Francis Church. Here we'll not only see the marvelous piece of art, but also learn a lot of the interesting facts and mysteries of its construction throughout the centuries. And as a bonus, we'll see an absolute architectural miracle:

After this experience, we will move to the center of the town, the Giraldinos square. Here you will have some free time to have lunch, and we would also recommend you to get your souvenirs now, if you want to keep warm memories about your experience with us.
Now it's time to get to know Portugals biggest Cathedral  Evoras Cathedral with the breathtaking panoramic view over the town!
Our next stop is the Roman Temple, being the most well-preserved Roman reminder on the Portuguese territory.
We will bring you back to your accommodation in Lisbon safe & sound, hoping to have a chance to enjoy your company one more time!

Get ready for an exciting and active adventure with our experienced guide. After pick up from your hotel, we will depart from Lisbon and go directly to Elvas, with a quick stop at the fortress of Santa Luzia (10:30).

Once in Elvas, we are going to see the ancient aqueduct that used to supply water to its inhabitants. But the main attraction and focus of our interest is the Fortress of Elvas, a marvelous star-shaped fortification that was used for defense purposes.

After the fortress of Elvas, we will have some free time. It is the ideal spot to have lunch and buy some local pastries. Here, well not only enjoy the environment but will also taste authentic Portuguese cuisine. To add a final touch to our experience, we will give you some free time, so you can try the local pastrie

fields.name_stop: The Church of Our Lady of Assumption
fields.description: Our next place of visit is the Church of Our Lady of Assumption. This Old Cathedral of Elvas is a religious building, located in Republic Square, and is a great example of the Manuelino architecture.

fields.name_stop: Fortress of Our Lady of Grace
fields.description: Finally, its time to see the example of military architecture in Portugal  the Fortress of Our Lady of Grace! The fortress of Elvas and the Fortress of Santa Luzia have earned the town multiple prizes in military architecture and have also earned the status of a World Heritage Site, protected by UNESCO.

We will bring you back to your accommodation in Lisbon safe & sound, hoping to have a chance to enjoy your company once again! Time on the road will fly by fast as well drive through the picturesque landscapes on our way back to your accommodation.

Get ready for an interesting walk around the capital of Portugal - Lisbon. Our meeting point is at the square of Marqus de Pombal, right beside the statue. You'll easily recognize our guide as it'll be wearing the brand shirt/polo.

We start our walk by going down Lisbons Champs-Elysees  Avenida da Liberdade. The creation of this boulevard was inspired by the real Champs-Elysees, and projected similar to it. Some of the most important squares in Portuguese history are located down the boulevard.

The squares of Restauradores, King Peter the 4th, and Figueira. These squares were, and still are the vital parts of Portuguese life, as they play important roles in the social, cultural, and commercial sectors.

Now it's time to head to Augusta Street, which goes from King Peter the 4th square, all the way to the commerce square, passing under Lisbons triumphal arch. Augusta Street was, and still is one of the main traditional boutique streets.

The finishing touch of our tour is a pleasant walk by the Tagus River to the Time Out Market. This spot is a perfect choice to have lunch or to buy Portuguese local products, as it is a local market and food court!
Our walk is over, and you can turn back to your accommodation in Lisbon safe & sound. We hope to have a chance to enjoy your company one more time!
Get ready for an exciting and active adventure with our experienced guide. We will begin the tour in the morning departing from Lisbon, and heading to the Monastery of Batalha.

The Monastery of Batalha, famous for its stunning architecture, is protected by UNESCO. It played an important role in the history of Portugal and nowadays is one of the greatest reminders of Medieval times.

Our next stop is the Holy Town of Fatima, one of the most important pilgrimage sites in the world. Cleanse yourself and pay homage to the Shrine of Our Lady of Fatima, where the appraisal of the Virgin Mary happened to three shepherd children.

Its time to take a break and have some rest. Our guide would recommend the perfect spot for lunch with excellent delicious cuisine. After what we expect to be an outstanding lunch, its time to enjoy the more famous attraction.

Our last destination is the Templar Town of Tomar, shrouded in history and mystery. Explore the Castle of Tomar, once the headquarters of the Knights Templar in Portugal. Visit the Convent of Christ, another UNESCO World Heritage Site, and marvel at its significance in Portuguese history.
Our trip is over, and its time to turn back to Lisbon. We will bring you back to your accommodation in Lisbon safe & sound, hoping to have a chance to enjoy your company one more time!

Get ready for an exciting and active adventure with our experienced guide. After pick up from your hotel, we will depart from Lisbon at the selected time and our first stop will be at the Monastery of Batalha. The time on the road will fly by fast as your comfort is our priority.

This amazing architectural landmark is protected by UNESCO, playing an important role in the history of Portugal, besides the incredible architectural significance. No big surprise, that its one of the most popular destinations among travelers around the globe. After a short half-hour drive we will get to Fatima.

Well see the most famous landmarks in Fatima. The Sanctuary is undoubtedly a must-visit place for hundreds of believers and non-religious people. This beautiful piece of architecture will astonish you, and you will see all the Portuguese architecture in its full glory!

Our guide will recommend the best places with excellent delicious cuisine. After what we expect to be an outstanding lunch, its time to move further. One more short trip with picturesque scenery, and we'll get to  Santarem.

Time is key in our itinerary, and we have plenty to observe. After lunch, we will make a final stop of our experience in the gothic capital of Portugal  Santarem! Of course, the town has earned this title due to the huge number of structures erected in the Gothic period there. A great finale to an exquisite day!
We will bring you back to your accommodation in Lisbon safe & sound, hoping to have a chance to enjoy your company one more time!

Get ready for an exciting and active adventure with our experienced guide. After pick up from your hotel, we will depart from Lisbon at the selected time and go directly to the Cape Espichel. The time on the road will fly fast because your comfort is our priority.
Our first stop is Cape Espichel, where we will have a quick stop for some pictures and to enjoy the fantastic landscape that can be found there!
After Cape Espichel, it's time to see the mountainside of Arrbida. Here we will have an amazing panoramic tour with some stops along the way, and take some pictures of the incredible view.
We will bring you back to your accommodation in Lisbon safe & sound, hoping to have a chance to enjoy your company one more time!

Get ready for an exciting and active adventure with our experienced guide. After pick up from your hotel, we will depart from Lisbon at the selected time and go directly to Obidos. The time on the road will fly by fast as your comfort is our priority.

Our first stop will be in Obidos  the most well-preserved medieval town in Portugal. We will visit all the main attractions in this charismatic town to feel its atmosphere and see all the beauty of local architecture, well-kept till our time.
After visiting Obidos, we will move to Peniche, a popular local destination for surfers. This will be the spot where we will have lunch, enjoying authentic Portuguese cuisine.
Our next stop is Baleal. Well have a nice soothing walk by the peninsula of Baleal in the most relaxing way possible. This place is a perfect spot to feel all the beauty of life without fuzz.

As a final touch of our visit, we will go to the home of the biggest surfed waves in the world  Nazare! Since Steven Mcnamarra surfed the 100-foot wave in Nazare, this place has become the top destination for world-class surfers.
We will bring you back to your accommodation in Lisbon safe & sound, hoping to have a chance to enjoy your company one more time!

fields.name_stop: Vasco da Gama Tower (Myriad by SANA Hotels)
fields.description: Our meeting point will be in front of the Vasco da Gama Tower - Myriad by SANA Hotels. It's easy to recognize our guide as he will be in the branded shirt/polo/hat. 15 minutes later, after the group is ready, our guide will take you on a pleasant walk by the Tagus River, surrounded by unique examples of contemporary ar
After a short walk, you will arrive at the first stop, the biggest indoor spectacle venue in Portugal  MEO Arena.

fields.name_stop: Vasco da Gama + Oriente Train Station
fields.description: Our next stop is a masterpiece by Santiago Calatrava, the Vasco da Gama shopping mall, connected with the Oriente train Station and Bus terminal.

Now it's time to take a short walk and return to the riverside, passing Lisbons Casino. We're heading to Portuguese National Pavilion, which is another important structure, projected by Portuguese architect Siza Vieira. This place hosts numerous exhibitions and other cultural events. This project was so successful tha
To finish our short walk we'll stop at Lisbons Aquarium  2nd biggest in Europe. It's the perfect choice for everybody who enjoys maritime life, which is a house for the most exotic aquatic species!
Our walk is over, and you can turn back to your accommodation in Lisbon safe & sound. Or you can have a pleasant lunch by the riverside! We hope to enjoy your company one more time!

Get ready for an exciting and active adventure with our experienced guide. After pick up, we will depart from Lisbon at the selected time and go straight to Sintra by a picturesque road with breathtaking views of the Atlantic Ocean.

The first stop is mystical Syntra, one of the most popular destinations among travelers around the globe. Well see the most famous landmarks in Sintra, one of which is an incredible architectural monument  the Pena Palace.

After leaving the Palace, its time to go to the center of the Old Town. The charming Old Town will be the perfect spot for lunch, as it provides diversity and quality. As for the local pastry from Sintra, it's amazing! Our guides will recommend the best places with excellent delicious cuisine.

As a real explorer, you will see the beauty of the wild cliffs, and feel the power of the ocean waves. Cabo de Roca is a cliff that stretches to the Atlantic Ocean, being the so-called, most western point of inland Europe. Here you have free time to get acquainted with the place, making the best memories.

It's the end of our busy day, and its time to return! Relax on the way back to Lisbon, as you go by the coastal towns of Cascais, Estoril, and Oeiras, among others. Here you will be able to witness all the Coastline from Cascais to Lisbon, until eventually the Ocean becomes the Tagus River, and Belm in the background

The first spot on our route is Almoroul Castle, accessible by boat. You will have some time to explore it and take amazing photos!

Its time to return home! Time on the road will fly by fast as well drive through the picturesque landscapes on our way back. We will bring you back to your accommodation in Lisbon safe & sound, hoping to have a chance to enjoy your company once again!

fields.name: Lisbon Oceanarium
fields.page_description: Lisbon Aquarium showcases diverse marine life in all its beauty, including a unique species. The huge central tank with sharks, rays, and other fascinating creatures is the main attraction.
fields.introduction_title: Lisbon Oceanarium: The Biggest in Europe
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
The Oceanarium in Lisbon, built in 1998, is one of the largest in the world, displaying more than 25 thousand marine life species. This place is perfect for an exciting family visit, and will certainly appeal not only to children but also to all adults who are not indifferent to the beauty and uniqueness of the underwater world. Lisbon Oceanarium is unique because it contains the inhabitants of all oceans without exception in one place. There is also a second building connected to the main one by a transparent gallery. The place is open not only to conduct excursions here but also to carry out serious scientific research on underwater flora and fauna.

On the ground floor, there are 25 aquariums where you can view marine inhabitants individually. And in the center of the second floor, there is a huge tank about seven meters deep. Even though the representatives of different climatic zones are separated by a transparent partition, it is almost imperceptible, which emphasizes the idea of the unity of the waters of the World Ocean. This floor is also occupied by four thematic aquariums - in each of them is recreated the flora and fauna of one of the oceans. The second building is educational, as it hosts exhibitions, events, and excursions dedicated to the protection and safety of species.
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
The huge sunfish is the main attraction of the Oceanarium since its maintenance requires strict conditions. Also in the Lisbon Oceanarium lives a giant Pacific octopus weighing about 250 kg and with a tentacle span of 9 meters.

The collection includes endangered species such as seahorses, octopuses, manta rays, and mobulas. The entire population is strictly protected by a research team that cares about the health and living conditions of the inhabitants. In the outdoor pools, you can meet vices and parrots, penguins, and otters.

The main focus of the activities held here are organized excursions, but the base also regularly hosts master classes, exhibitions, concerts, and shows. The main purpose of most exhibitions is scientific and social activities, within which one can learn about endangered species of animals and the impact of human activities on the ecology of the seas. Some events are purely entertaining. In addition, it is possible to organize events upon individual request.
fields.short_introduction_text: Lisbon Aquarium showcases diverse marine life in all its beauty, including a unique species. The huge central tank with sharks, rays, and other fascinating creatures is the main attraction.
fields.info_subtitle: Lisbon Oceanarium is the door to a world of 8,000 marine inhabitants, highlighting the wonder and majesty of the marine life

fields.name: St. George's Castle
fields.page_description: The Castle of St. George is the heart of the Portuguese capital, the history of which began at the turn of two eras.
fields.introduction_title: St. George's Castle in Lisbon: An Object of Lisbon Cultural Heritage and Notable Attraction
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
The Castle of St. George is the heart of the Portuguese capital, the history of which began at the turn of two eras. In 1147, it was liberated by the Crusaders from the Moors. Afonso Henriques, the commander of the Crusaders, became the first ruler of the country. Then, until the 16th century, the castle was the official royal residence.

Outstanding architecture and history made the castle one of the symbols of the country, a great introduction to medieval history for tourists. The complex is memorable for its calm atmosphere and solemnity, perfect for the Lisbon city walking tour. It mesmerizes with gorgeous panoramic views of Lisbon with red-tiled roofs and the Tagus River. As for the collection of cannons and an archaeological museum, it's more than impressive.

From the top of the hill, there are open views of the ancient part of the city and houses with tiled roofs. The monument to the first king Afonso, who holds a shield and sword in his hands, is also located here. The castle went through numerous buildings and changed many times, the last time it was restored in the 20th century.
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
The fortress is presented not just by one castle, but by an ancient town, a popular destination for day tours from Lisbon. Visitors can see preserved fragments of medieval battlements, walking through the inner parks of olive trees of this magnificent landmark of Portugal. When Vasco da Gama returned from sea voyages, the celebration was here, as well as various significant events for the kingdom. The towers are open for visitors, so everyone has the opportunity to climb and take a walk along the fortress walls. 

For a more interactive experience, it's recommended to pay attention to the numerous multimedia exhibitions, held here every day. The Castle of St. George in Lisbon suffered badly from an earthquake in the 16th and 18th centuries. However, the fortress walls have been restored and are in good condition. In the Tower of Odysseus, for example, you can see panoramas of Lisbon, and an archaeological museum is located in one of the old wings of the fortress. Projected images on the walls show the major city's historical events, such as a simulated earthquake, the return of Vasco da Gama, the fall of the Church of Carmo, and much more, from the era of the Inquisition to the period of the Salazar dictatorship.
fields.short_introduction_text: Discover a stunning palace, a significant architectural and historical spot, one of the must-see things in Portugal. St. George's Castle is a great example of late Baroque architecture with typical decorations.
fields.info_subtitle: The Fortress of St. George is one of the main ancient landmarks in Lisbon and a top must-see spot

fields.name: Tram 28
fields.page_description: The iconic yellow tram route is a visiting card of the city. It goes through the historic districts of Lisbon, offering a charming and nostalgic journey through picturesque neighborhoods that showcase Lisbon's daily life.
fields.introduction_title: Lisbon's Iconic Tram 28: The Authentic Lisbon Tram Experience and Key Stops on the Route
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
The yellow tram with the number 28 has become a symbol of the city and an interesting journey for Lisbon tours through the streets of the old city. It can be seen on postcards and leaflets as a well-known and charming attraction in Portugal, the same as Sintra castle or Nazare waves. The trip is fun for all categories of tourists, but it should be noted that it's not only touristic but also an active transport route for locals, so it can be quite busy.

The length of the route is 7 kilometers, and the journey takes from 40 to 60 minutes. For almost a century now, this tram has been tightly connected with the streets of Lisbon, perfectly fitting into the urban landscape and being its significant feature. The last modernization of the tram took place in the mid-90s. The emphasis was on the technical part, and the appearance is still as close as possible to the original.

If you want to take a seat, the best place for the beginning of tram route No. 28 is Martim Moniz Square. The route has existed for more than a century, during which it has remained virtually unchanged. The carriages are equipped with wooden seats.
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
To inform the driver about a stop, simply pull the rope in the cabin. In some parts of the route, the streets are so narrow that passengers can reach out and touch the walls of houses.

As for the route itself, it's the main reason for the popularity of this tram among tourists and an answer to why many visitors choose this option instead of the Lisbon bus tour. For one ride, you can see the most significant spots in Lisbon. In general, the route is a funny experience that should be included in Lisbon tours. Starting from Martim Moniz Square, Lisbon's scenic tram journey passes through the Mouraria quarter, the historic Tram 28 route passes through the Alfama quarter, the Temple of Santa Engracia, the Cathedral of Se, the Lisbon Cathedral, the Castle of St. George, the Santa Luzia observation deck, Plaza Commerce with the Arc de Triomphe, the Parliament Building, Baisha, Camoens Square, Santa Justa Elevator, Chiado, and Estrela Basilica. 

You should note that it's possible to get off at any stop, walk, look around and enjoy the city, and then get on the next one. Since there is only one railway track, the tram does not run often, approximately every 45–50 minutes. The last station, Campo de Ourique, is outside of Lisbon's historic center, so either jump off early or plan a return trip along the same route. Or walk back on foot, as walking around Lisbon is a pleasure!
fields.short_introduction_text: The iconic yellow tram route is a visiting card of the city. It goes through the historic districts of Lisbon, offering a charming and nostalgic journey through picturesque neighborhoods that showcase Lisbon's daily life.
fields.info_subtitle: Lisbon Tram 28 is the way to immerse yourself in the nostalgic past of Lisbon's historical streets and one of the must-see things in Lisbon

fields.name: Jeronimos Monastery
fields.page_description: Jeronimos Monastery, opened in 1495, is one of the most significant places in Lisbon, a sign of the era of prosperity of Portugal during the Age of Discovery, and a must-see place in the Lisbon city walking tour.
fields.introduction_title: Jeronimos Monastery: UNESCO World Heritage Object in Lisbon
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
Jeronimos Monastery, opened in 1495, is one of the most significant places in Lisbon, a sign of the era of prosperity of Portugal during the Age of Discovery, and a must-see place in the Lisbon city walking tour. The facade of the monastery, made of soft beige sandstone, looks luxurious against the backdrop of spacious green gardens. In the west wing of the monastery is the Maritime Museum with Vasco da Gama Resting Place and the National Archaeological Museum of Portugal, making it a great choice for a full-day excursion. 

The first floor of the monastery is impressive with its luxurious, well-kept interiors. The specific feature on the second floor is a unique carving, elegant and sophisticated. Today the monastery is a big museum, but also it's used for the state purposes of the country and the world. The famous Treaty of Lisbon was signed here. 

All the parts of the monastery are unique, some of the columns show sea knots, sea monsters, corals, and many other marine motifs. That's why this attraction is always in the top places to visit for day trips from Lisbon. The greatest masters of stone carving expressed their art, creating one of Lisbon's architectural wonders, capturing scenes from the life of St. Jerome and the coat of arms of the king.
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
A sculpture of Henry the Navigator, holding a sword in his hands, is located near the middle column, and stone lions are fighting at his feet. Archangel Gabriel, who is the guardian of Portugal, crowns the top of the portal. Today, the monastery is one of the major attractions of Portugal.

The Church of Santa Maria, located here, is an architectural masterpiece and a must-see place in the list of Belem district attractions. The church, with its genuine architectural style, can be called the heart of the Jeronimos Monastery. It amazes with its rich decor, soft light emanating from narrow lancet stained-glass windows, twisted columns reminiscent of scaffolding, a mesh vault, an abundance of bas-reliefs, and statues of saints and apostles in niches.

A visit to the Maritime Museum as a part of Lisbon tours will give both adult and young visitors an unforgettable experience as every exhibit seems to be imbued with the sea breeze and adventure. At the National Archaeological Museum, visitors will see the remains of the great events. The abundance of decorative elements in every corner of the monastery complex is impressive.
fields.short_introduction_text: Jeronimos Monastery, opened in 1495, is one of the most significant places in Lisbon, a sign of the era of prosperity of Portugal during the Age of Discovery, and a must-see place in the Lisbon city walking tour.
fields.info_subtitle: Lisbon Jeronimos Monastery is the national shrine of Portugal and one of the most beautiful Lisbon cultural landmarks of the Middle Ages

fields.name: Alfama District
fields.page_description: Alfama is a colorful mix of narrow streets, authentic houses, and Fado music in the air. The oldest district in Lisbon, it has its own unique historical charm with breathtaking views of the city.
fields.introduction_title: The Colorful Alfama: Travel Tips and Things to Do in the Historical Disctrict of Lisbon
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
The Alfama district can easily be called the “soul” of Lisbon, as it's the most colorful, unique, and popular area of the Portuguese capital, and one of the spots for the Lisbon city walking tour. Alfama was the only area that survived the earthquake in 1755 and preserved its medieval spirit to this day. The entire area is located on rocky hills and consists of small narrow streets, along which you can walk endlessly. It belongs to the old part of the city, so within its borders are located the largest number of must-see attractions. Walking through this area, immerse yourself in the fascinating history of the old city, and pay special attention to such Alfama Lisbon attractions:

Se Cathedral is an iconic Lisbon symbol built on the site of an old Moorish mosque, which resembles an enemy fortress with massive towers. The building is well-kept from the Middle Ages, allowing one to appreciate the mystery of the Gothic style.

The National Museum of Azulejos is one of the most notable features of Lisbon. Small decorative clay tiles are on almost every building in the city center. The Azulejo Museum is the best idea for day trips from Lisbon to know the history of art and creation
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
The Fortress of St. George is the surviving wall of an ancient defensive structure. It is located on the top of a hill, so you can enjoy not only the beauty of the ancient building but also the incomparable view of the city.

National Pantheon of Santa Engracia. It's one of the visit cards of Alfama, as its huge snow-white dome tower is visible from many points. 

Monastery of San Vicente de Fora is a significant religious attraction, and picturesque site in the area, harmoniously blending into the panorama of the city.

The area presents a wide range of observation platforms, which are considered the best Alfama Lisbon photography spots. The most interesting of them are Miradouro de Santa Luzia, Miradouro Sophia de Mello Breyner Andresen, Miradouro das Portas do Sol Observation Deck, and many others. You may find a lot of things to visit in Lisbon in other places, but in Alfama they are especially magnificent.

The Alfama district will create an unforgettable impression of Portugal's historical sites. In the evening, you can hear the sounds of romances throughout the area, as the best singers perform in cafes and restaurants, where it is highly advisable to spend time with a glass of local wine.
fields.short_introduction_text: Alfama is a colorful mix of narrow streets, authentic houses, and Fado music in the air. The oldest district in Lisbon, it has its own unique historical charm with breathtaking views of the city.
fields.info_subtitle: Alfama district Lisbon is a delightful mix of the charming atmosphere of an old Portugal city, combined with cultural richness

fields.name: Praca do Comercio
fields.page_description: Praca do Comercio, founded in the 15th century, is the place where Lisbon's development, connected with the time of great geographical discoveries, started.
fields.introduction_title: Visit Praca do Comercio: One of the Most Significant Lisbon's Landmarks
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
Praca do Comercio, founded in the 15th century, is the place where Lisbon's development, connected with the time of great geographical discoveries, started. The first name, Palace Square, is connected with the first building on it, the royal palace of Ribeira. Then was an international maritime trade stage, when a port appeared, a shipyard, India House, and other administrative buildings along the river. However, the proximity to the water during the earthquake ruined Palace Square.

Nowadays, in the center of the square stands an equestrian statue of the Portuguese King Jose I, who was the head of the country during these troubled times and restored the city from scratch.

The Arc de Triomphe serves as a kind of gateway to the square. By the way, there is an excellent observation deck on it, where you can climb and look down on the Trade Square when you go on the Lisbon city walking tour. During various city events, a stage, screens, and tents are installed here, and the square has become one of the busiest Portuguese plazas in the city. By the way, on weekdays there are very few people here although it may seem so because of its enormous size. On weekends, Commerce Square hosts all sorts of events, including street performers.
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
Evidence of the fact that there was once a royal palace is a pair of symmetrical houses near the water, the design of which is very reminiscent of the towers of a ruined castle. One of them now houses the Lisbon Museum. Another echo from palace times and Lisbon's cultural heritage is the marble staircase flanked by two columns (Cais das Colunas). According to one version, the staircase existed before the earthquake and led directly to the palace. For many years, it served to receive important guests, including Queen Elizabeth II of England. Well, now this is a favorite place for locals and tourists to watch the sunset.

The square opens up a panoramic view of the Tagus River and a breathtaking view of the 25th of April Bridge. It is one of the most beautiful tourist spots in Lisbon, especially at sunset. In terms of day trips from Lisbon, stroll along the 18th-century houses and the promenade, visit the Arc de Triomphe viewpoint, and listen to street musicians perform. It's highly recommended to try the national dishes of Portugal at Martinho da Arcada, one of the oldest restaurants in Lisbon, located here. You can also use a ferry to enter Lisbon through the Palace Square, as kings and queens did, by sailing to the pier by the Tagus River.
fields.short_introduction_text: Praca do Comercio, founded in the 15th century, is the place where Lisbon's development, connected with the time of great geographical discoveries, started.
fields.info_subtitle: Discover Praca do Comercio, one of the top things to visit in Lisbon, the soul and heart of the Portuguese capital

fields.name: Belem Tower
fields.page_description: One of the most beautiful symbols of Lisbon is the Belem Tower. The majestic structure stands right next to the water, creating an incredibly picturesque view of the historical part of the city - Belem.
fields.introduction_title: Belem Tower in Lisbon: Discover Belem Tower UNESCO Site and Cultural Heritage
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
One of the most beautiful symbols of Lisbon is the Belem Tower. The majestic structure stands right next to the water, creating an incredibly picturesque view of the historical part of the city - Belem.

The tower is one of the most popular landmarks in Portugal. At the end of the 80s, it was declared a cultural heritage monument, included in the UNESCO lists, and is under its protection. This point is one of the most significant spots for Lisbon city walking tour. The construction of the tower was carried out in 1514-1519 and is associated with the Age of Discovery, in which Portugal and Lisbon itself played one of the leading roles.

Since 1515, the tower has welcomed Lisbon sailors returning to their hometown with Venetian arcades, an abundance of architectural decoration, and a statue of Our Lady of Prosperous Returns, the patroness of Portuguese sailors since the time of Vasco da Gama. It’s worth coming here to admire the amazing architecture, see the collection of ancient cannons in casemates, see unusual sculptures of rhinoceroses, and enjoy the views of the river.
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
The Belem Tower architecture is unique, as it is massive and at the same time elegant structure, consisting of the observation tower itself and a powerful bastion at its foot, jutting into the natural harbor at the entrance to the city. As you approach the tower on your day trips from Lisbon, whether from the city or along the river, you will gradually discover all its amazing details. The architectural style in which this structure is made is called Manueline, which became widespread exclusively in Portugal, during its heyday as a maritime power. This style includes elements of Gothic, Renaissance, Moorish, and even a little Indian style. Basically, everything that the Portuguese were able to see thanks to their numerous expeditions. A true master, Francisco de Arruda, is the author of this magnificent architecture. 

The fortress consists of two parts: a five-story tower with statues of St. Michael and St. Vincent, equipped with a stunning Templar chapel, which is located inside, and a hexagonal bastion with 17 cannons. On the ground floor of the tower (bastion level). While going on Lisbon tours, it is worth exploring the open terrace from which the monarch himself once greeted returning travelers. Here is a statue of the Virgin Mary of Safe Returns, and the perimeter of the terrace is decorated with Moorish turrets reminiscent of exotic headdresses.

fields.name: Azulejo Museum
fields.page_description: Azulejos are clay tiles, painted and covered with glaze, considered to be a traditional decorative material in Portugal and Spain. It came to Spain from Arab countries in the 15th century.
fields.introduction_title: National Azulejo Museum: One of the Most Colorful Lisbon Cultural Attractions
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
Azulejos are clay tiles, painted and covered with glaze, considered to be a traditional decorative material in Portugal and Spain. It came to Spain from Arab countries in the 15th century. 

Traditionally, the tiles were colorful, but when the fashion for Dutch tiles spread across Europe in the 17th century, the azulejos also changed and still remain more often two-color white and blue. 

Azulejos can still be seen in the oldest monasteries in the country. Many eastern countries also use them, and if you have ever seen mosques lined with beautiful brightly painted glazed tiles, then this is the prototype of azulejos.

Traditional Portuguese azulejos are kept in the museum, located in the historical building of the Monastery of the Mother of God (Mosteiro da Madre de Deus), a perfect destination in terms of walking tours in Lisbon, Portugal. 

An old 16th-century monastery has an interesting history, because, in addition to the function of the monastery, it also became a place where you can see unique tile paintings from antiquity to modern times, brought from different countries.
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
The museum allows the visitor to contemplate a diverse collection of tiles, with products from different eras dating back more than 500 years to the present day. The museum itself is divided into several halls, visiting each of them you can understand the history and stages of development of this ancient art form.

The building also has majestic decoration, with most of the walls covered in hundreds of azulejos. The visitor can also see the Igreja Madre de Dues church through the glass, as shown in the photo. The decoration of gilded wood carvings is impressive.

This is perhaps one of Lisbon's lesser-known museums, and because it is located further from the historical center, outside the Baisha-Chiado area, it is often missed by tourists passing through Lisbon. 

But it is undoubtedly one of the most important museums in Portugal and is worth a visit anyway. This is an excellent program for day trips from Lisbon for the whole family and a unique place to feel the atmosphere of that time and see it through the eyes of a master.

Today, the Church of Madre de Deus is an integral part of the National Tile Museum, an important repository of the memory of Portuguese culture, and a notable place in the list of things to visit in Lisbon. The location is a perfect choice for everybody who is looking for a non-standard tourist program. 

The museum keeps an extensive collection that explains how tiles are made, their history, trends, and other important aspects related to this decorative and symbolic element.
fields.short_introduction_text: Azulejos are clay tiles, painted and covered with glaze, considered to be a traditional decorative material in Portugal and Spain. It came to Spain from Arab countries in the 15th century.
fields.info_subtitle: Azulejo historic tile exhibits authentic craft tiles, showing the history of Portuguese art in all its prosperity

fields.name: Senhora do Monte
fields.page_description: One of the must-visit places for a Lisbon city walking tour is the Miradouro da Senhora do Monte observation deck. It may be a challenge to get there on foot, but its worth it as the breathtaking views over the city are guaranteed.
fields.introduction_title: Senhora do Monte Viewpoint in Lisbon: Top Spot for the Scenic Views of the City
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
One of the must-visit places for a Lisbon city walking tour is the Miradouro da Senhora do Monte observation deck. It may be a challenge to get there on foot, but it’s worth it as the breathtaking views over the city are guaranteed. 

The viewpoint is one of the places where the visitors can look from above at the tiled roofs and architecture of the buildings and feel like they’ve traveled 100 years back. The entire old city is spread out in front with a panorama of such popular attractions, as the Sao Jorge Castle, the Statue of Christ, the 25th of April Bridge, the Santa Justa ski lift, and the Carmo Monastery.

The easiest way to come here is on foot from the Intendente metro station. Although the path may seem a little steep, the panorama is worth every step.
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
Miradouro da Senhora do Monte is one of the most popular spots to enjoy the best Lisbon panoramas and the tranquility, feeling the atmosphere of the old city. The viewpoint, surrounded by beautiful trees and cozy benches, is an easy escape from the crowds and noise of the big city. This is the perfect place for a romantic sunset with your nearest and dearest, or relaxation after exploring the city.

One more famous attraction, located here, is the chapel of Nossa Senhora do Monte. The visitors shouldn’t miss the opportunity to see one of the most beautiful Portugal landmarks, dating back to the times of the Roman Empire, as it can add a final touch to the unforgettable impression of Lisbon. In 1147 a chapel was built in honor of St. Gens, the hermit, who was one of the first bishops of Lisbon. In the same place, he suffered martyrdom, after which he was canonized. 

A bit later the Augustinian monks installed the marble chair of St. Gens in the chapel. There is an interesting legend that highly recommends pregnant women to come here. It says that If a woman who is waiting for the baby sits on this chair, she can give birth easily and without complications. Even the wife of King Joao V of Portugal, Donna Maria Anna of Austria, followed this advice when she was pregnant with the heir to the throne. This tradition is carefully kept to this day
fields.short_introduction_text: One of the must-visit places for a Lisbon city walking tour is the Miradouro da Senhora do Monte observation deck. It may be a challenge to get there on foot, but its worth it as the breathtaking views over the city are guaranteed.

fields.name: Gulbenkian Museum
fields.page_description: This museum in Lisbon demonstrates an exquisite collection of art, dedicated to various cultures and periods. Get a diverse artistic experience, exploring ancient artifacts and modern masterpieces.
fields.introduction_title: The Calouste Gulbenkian Museum: One of the Most Significant Lisbon Art Exhibitions
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
The Calouste Gulbenkian Museum is an art exhibition in Lisbon with a solid collection of European fine art and ancient artworks. It was opened on October 2, 1969, by Calouste Gulbenkian, an Armenian billionaire who donated a priceless collection of works of art from Europe, Asia, and Africa to the Portuguese capital.

While the museum is a cultural attraction, the surrounding park is a bright example of a landscape design with numerous rest zones. The visit here is a great idea for the vacation of all family members. For the Portuguese, the museum art collection in Lisbon is a source of pride, and for tourists, it is a must-see place for day trips from Lisbon to explore the city and country.

The exhibits are brilliant, and each of them deserves special attention. The list of names of artists whose works are exhibited in the museum is overwhelming. In addition to paintings, the Gulbenkian Museum in Lisbon also presents decorative items and sculptures from Egypt, Persia, and Greece. 

Here are available rare ancient books and antique furniture from France. The museum complex is on the list of the World's most famous and richest museums. There are also many Art Deco items in the museum: jewelry, a collection of glass, and decorative objects
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
The collection of exhibits includes more than 6 thousand items with about one thousand on display. The focus of attention is the Lalique part of the collection dating to the 11th-20th centuries. Additionally, there are many medieval items. The collection of medieval books and manuscripts occupies a separate room.

But most of the visitors come here to see the paintings, and it’s the main reason why the museum is one of the brightest cultural attractions of Lisbon. Original canvases by Rembrandt, Rubens, and Van Eyck are presented here. A big part of the collection is made of the paintings of English artists, such as Turner and Gainsborough. Additionally, there is a large collection of impressionists, including paintings by Claude Monet, Renoir, and Degas. And besides the above, there is a huge number of less famous, but no less talented painters.

The museum has a large collection of antique furniture and an even larger collection of gold and silver objects: jewelry, decorative, and for home use. A special place is occupied by the collection of Armenian and Middle Eastern art. 

Some tourists come to the Museu Calouste Gulbenkian to visit one of the Lisbon cultural activities held here. After the visit, it’s highly recommended to walk through the garden which is a well-maintained recreation area with numerous sculptures.

fields.name: Vasco da Gama Bridge
fields.page_description: Vasco da Gama Bridge in Lisbon was opened in 1996 and nowadays is one of the most impressive landmarks of the Portuguese capital. The architectural structure is a striking combination of functionality with beauty and grace.
fields.introduction_title: Vasco da Gama Bridge: One of The Most Significant Landmarks in Lisbon
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
Vasco da Gama Bridge in Lisbon was opened in 1996 and nowadays is one of the most impressive landmarks of the Portuguese capital. The architectural structure is a striking combination of functionality with beauty and grace. The capacity of the regular six-lane highway is up to 52,000 vehicles. As for the periods when the traffic load increases several times, there are 2 more additional lanes.

The length of the bridge is 17.2 km and the width is 30 meters. It was built to reduce traffic on Lisbon's first bridge, known as the 25 April Bridge. The project was carried out after taking into account a set of factors that could affect the performance, safety, and service life of the structure, such as the characteristics of the bottom topography and the landscapes of the northern and southern banks of the Tagus, environmental, and aesthetic aspects. 

The bridge was created by the French engineer Michel Virlojo. He managed to carry out an amazing project, taking into account all the nuances of safe construction, fitting it perfectly into the landscape, and keeping the ecological balance of the environment
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
The Vasco da Gama Bridge in Lisbon is recognized as a real miracle of modern engineering. It makes a lasting impression on the audience, and it should be seen within Lisbon tours to create a full impression of the city. It's definitely the most stunning among Portuguese bridges. To see the bridge in all its beauty it's recommended to have a look from the embankment, from the Park of Nations, from the cable car cabins. Those who are keen on active sports can have a look from a paraglider. Wonderful photos and videos against the backdrop of the gigantic structure are guaranteed.

For two decades, it occupied first place in the ranking of the longest bridges in Europe. When entering, the opposite side is not visible, creating the illusion of infinity. That part of the structure which passes over the Park of Nations is one of the most striking attractions of the capital of Portugal. 

Bridge design and architecture make a special impression at night as soft luminous points are reflected in the water. The bridge is modern and safe, but the route is often used by local street racers, who cause large-scale car accidents. 

The entrance on the bridge is chargeable because the funds for the construction of this attraction were allocated by the Lusoponte consortium, which received a 40-year concession. However, a high-speed trip on a broadband highway and wonderful views are worth spending a certain amount of money and time on traveling across the bridge
fields.short_introduction_text: Vasco da Gama Bridge in Lisbon was opened in 1996 and nowadays is one of the most impressive landmarks of the Portuguese capital. The architectural structure is a striking combination of functionality with beauty and grace.
fields.info_subtitle: Vasco da Gama Bridge is one of the greatest historical landmarks in Portugal, the perfect fusion of architecture and functionality

fields.name: Chiado
fields.page_description: Chiado is a vibrant and upscale neighborhood in central Lisbon. It's well-known for its trendy shops, theaters, and cafes. Tourists are attracted to this neighborhood because it combines a lively atmosphere with historical charm.
fields.introduction_title: Chiado: One of the Most Vibrant Districts in Lisbon
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
Chiado is one of the oldest neighborhoods in the Portuguese capital, located right in its heart, between Bairro Alto and the center of Baixa Pombalina.

The appearance of the name of the district goes back to the 16th century. Some say that the area got its name after the poet António Ribeiro (1520-1591), whose statue can be seen in the main square. According to another version, the name was given in honor of Gaspar Dias, who ran a pub on Rua Paiva Andrade. Both had the nickname “Shiado”, which can be translated as “sneaky”.

This elegant district is an intellectual center of Lisbon, which houses numerous theaters, antique shops, and bookstores. In the 19th century, this district was especially popular among writers who formed an unforgettable Bohemian atmosphere. It's highly recommended to walk through the main shopping street of Chiado, Rua Garett, which is full of antique shops. The Basilica of Nossa Senhora dos Martires, built in 1147, is the historical and architectural landmark of the street. Even though most of the buildings in Chiado are dated back to the 18th century, they were destroyed in a fire in 1988.

The renovation was carried out by the Portuguese architect Alvaro Siza Vieira. As a result of his work a unique architectural ensemble of new and restored buildings was created.
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
For example, in old times Chiado was used as the shortcut of the city to the surrounding farms and monasteries. The gates of the ancient fortress walls were built in the 14th century by order of King Fernando in the square of two churches, Our Lady of Loreto and Our Lady of the Incarnation. Nowadays, after the restoration, the fragments of these walls are the elements of some city buildings. 

The boundaries of the area are not clear as there are no walls or strict divisions by the streets. But it is quite clear that the Chiado area includes Largo do Carmo Square, Rua Garrett Street with the Church of the Martyrs, Camoes, and the Largo Trindade Coelho squares with the Church of Saint Roca. 

Chiado is rich not only in historical landmarks but also in culture. Not far from the theater district, there is another attraction, the Chiado Museum with rare exhibitions which definitely deserve attention. 

The best idea to explore the area is on foot as it's relatively small. While walking, the visitors should visit local shops, some of which are at least a hundred years old, and then have a rest in one of the fancy cafes to feel the atmosphere of the place.

If you stay here overnight, go to the neighboring Upper District (Bairro Alto). This area, with small streets full of bars and restaurants for every taste, is one of the most popular and crowded places in the city at night.

fields.name: The Quake Museum
fields.page_description: The Quake Museum is an interactive exhibition where visitors can explore the science of earthquakes and their impacts on Portugal in 1755. This immersive simulator and educational center is dedicated to natural disasters.
fields.introduction_title: The Quake Museum: An Interactive Earthquake Center
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
The Quake Museum is a new interactive attraction for the whole family in Lisbon, founded by Mayor Carlos Moidas. It is a space with a total area of 1,800 square meters with numerous options for entertainment. The implementation of the project cost 8 million euros, and today everyone has the opportunity to feel the atmosphere of the 1755 earthquake.

This thematic experience offers many options for maximum immersion in the atmosphere of 18th-century Lisbon. The immersive program includes several rooms where visitors can experience the full spectrum of the earthquake. The creators managed to successfully combine history, science, and emotions, making the attraction interesting for visitors of all ages.

A high level of interactivity is reached by using new technologies to transport visitors back to the day when Lisbon suffered from an earthquake. At that time it was the fourth largest city in the world, but natural disasters radically changed the situation.
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
The attraction is a unique chance to make a journey in a time machine, discovering the mysteries of the city that was lost, but then rebuilt in all its beauty the way we know it today. The interactive displays demonstrate the seismic activity while the visitors are walking by the streets of old Lisbon.

Through a scientific and historical perspective, the visitors will know everything about the earthquake's effects in Lisbon, same as the facts about the social leaders and villains who played key roles in the reconstruction. You'll also experience an earthquake in a Quake simulator, a room built using the latest technology to provide a shaky but safe experience.

But the main part of the journey is the simulator. The unique room was created to let the visitors feel the experience of a real earthquake, being safe and protected at the same time.

The Lisbon Earthquake Museum is an invitation to discover the wonders and horrors of that era and watch the drama unfold before your eyes.
fields.short_introduction_text: The Quake Museum is an interactive exhibition where visitors can explore the science of earthquakes and their impacts on Portugal in 1755. This immersive simulator and educational center is dedicated to natural disasters.

fields.name: The Monument of the Discoveries
fields.page_description: The Monument to the Discoveries is a sculpture of famous Portuguese explorers, and is a symbol of a tribute to the history of maritime and the most influential adventurers.
fields.introduction_title: The Monument of the Discoveries: The Memorial Sculpture Beside the Tagus River
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
Portugal is one of the countries that played an important role in world politics, being a country deeply involved in international relationships. The Portuguese made a significant contribution to the era of the Great Geographical Discoveries. Centuries later for the sake of memory of the discoverers on the shores of the Atlantic Ocean was created the majestic monument, which is now very popular with tourists.

The Monument of the Discoverers is located in the Lisbon suburb of Belem, so it's easy to include it in the visit around the city. The height of the monument is 52 meters, and the width is 20 meters, so it’s visible from a distance. 

The monument was created in 1960, on the 500th anniversary of the death of Henry the Navigator, and is still one of the visit cards of Lisbon. This is a copy of the monument created by the order of Antonio Salazar for the exhibition “Representation of the Portuguese World” in 1940 and dismantled 18 years later. The monument is made of concrete, and the sculptures are additionally decorated with limestones.

This attraction is fully dedicated to significant figures from the era of the Great Geographical Discoveries - navigators, writers, poets, and other important people.
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
Basically, the shape of the Monument of the Discoveries is a caravel, the bow of which hangs over the river and is crowned with a nine-meter statue of Henry the Navigator with a boat in his hands. Under the stone, sails stand sculptures of figures from the Age of Discovery, a time when Portugal was an influential world power. 

Among the detailed figures of rulers, navigators, scientists, cartographers, poets, missionaries, and other figures of the 15-16th century, you can see, for example, Vasco da Gama, Prince Pedro, Luis de Camoes, Pedro Alvares Cabral, Afonso de Albuquerque. In total, there are 32 sculptures on both decks of the caravel, each seven meters in height.

There is an elevator inside the monument that takes you to the observation deck. From above you can see a mosaic depicting a wind rose with a diameter of 50 meters and a map of the world, from here a panoramic view opens.

In addition, in the basement of the monument, there is a small exhibition dedicated to the Portuguese colonies.
fields.short_introduction_text: The Monument to the Discoveries is a sculpture of famous Portuguese explorers, and is a symbol of a tribute to the history of maritime and the most influential adventurers.

fields.name: The National Palace of Ajuda
fields.page_description: The Palace of Ajuda is a stunning example of Neoclassical architecture and an object of the rich cultural heritage of Portugal.
fields.introduction_title: The National Palace of Ajuda: The Castle and Royal Treasure Museum
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
The National Palace of Ajuda is one of the most beautiful palaces in Lisbon. This building in Neoclassical style was built in the first half of the 19th century. For that period of time, the palace was too grandiose and needed additional investments, so it could not be completed.

The location for the creation of the castle was chosen after the earthquake, which took place in 1755. But all the members of the royal family were safe. As a result of the incident, the king was so impressed that he paid special attention to a safe location for his palace. In order to make it more resistant, it was built out of wood. But the wooden palace was still burnt down by fire, and the next project was built of stone.

In 1862, under the direction of the architect Joaquim Possidonio Narciso da Silva, the unfinished palace received a new life. The major transformations touched the interior decoration of the palace, according to the ideas of the bourgeoisie of the 19th century, being aimed at improving the level of comfort.

The Royal Palace of Ajuda was the official residence of the Portuguese monarchy, being used for official ceremonies, grand balls, and banquets. After the proclamation of the Republic in 1910, the palace was closed until 1968, when it got a new life and was opened for visitors as a museum.
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
In 2018, a new reconstruction of the building was made. It included the reconstruction of the west wing. There was installed the vault of the Royal Treasure Museum. Nowadays the museum exhibits a collection of more than a thousand unique artworks, including luxury Portuguese Crown Jewels.

The renovation project was designed by the architect Joao Carlos Santos. The modern version of Ajuda Palace includes 34 museum halls, which reproduce the environment in which the Portuguese monarchs lived, showing it with historical accuracy and close attention to the details.

The magnificent collection includes furniture, porcelain, crystal, priceless tapestries, chandeliers, jewelry, and various decorative and functional items made using advanced technologies of their time (XV-XIX centuries). All the presented options can be seen and photographed.

The National Palace of Ajuda is often the place for official ceremonies and ceremonial acts of the Presidency of the Republic. One more additional idea on how to spend time here is to visit Ajuda Botanical Garden, a small but amazingly picturesque place with endemic species and modern landscape design
